    "created_at": "2018-08-22T14:14:20Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-08-22T14:14:20Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "I've been having a lot of feedback from other users at my company who get frustrated that this isn't the default behavior (both for `%%script` and `!` patterns). For example `!pip install -U package-that-does-not-exist` will not halt execution, but this is a common pattern that cannot assume success to continue execution.\r\n\r\nHow disruptive would it be if we changed the default behavior to raise an error for nonzero exit codes by default?"
  },
